ShipAI::CheckPowerLevels

(This controls what systems the ship powers)

First, it turns all systems off, as far as it can (respecting ion power
locking, hacking, etc).

Next it allocates one power to several systems, in order:
* Oxygen
* Teleporter
* Clonebay
* Medbay, but only if bHurtCrew is set on CrewAI - see doc/crew-ai

There's then a big loop to allocate the rest of the power:

If the ship is hostile and not escaping, power up one weapon. If there's a
weapon that's powered off that's playing it's firing animation, use that.

Otherwise, loop through all the powered-off weapons, and keep track of the
weapon that has been charging for the longest. There's a major bit of
weirdness, however. When the charge time is stored, it's rounded down, as
shown in this pseudocode:

bestWeapon = null
bestWeaponTime = -1
for weapon in poweredOffWeapons:
    if weapon.chargingTime > bestWeaponTime:
        bestWeaponTime = roundDown(weapon.chargingTime)
        bestWeapon = weapon

This means that unless the weapons have all been charging for an integer
amount of time (which in practice means they were off until now), they'll
strongly prefer weapons that appear in the list later (further to the right,
if the enemy had a weapons panel like the player) if there's multiple weapons
with the same charge time.

This also means that the AI will swap weapon powers, if a weapon has just fired
and another was was powered off but hasn't yet lost all it's charge.

Next, and also with the hostile-and-not-escaping check, attempt to power up
a drone.

Then attempt to power up shields, cloaking, and engines, in that order.

This loop repeats until no more power was added to any of drones, shields,
cloaking, or engines. This notably excludes weapons - thus this loop can
end if the ship has one shield/engine and three weapons, with only two of
the weapons turned on.

Finally, go through each system in this order and try to add as much power
to it as possible:

Shields, Engines, Oxygen, Weapons, Drone, Medbay, Teleporter, Cloaking,
Artillery, Clonebay, Mind Control, Hacking

(this is just the numerical order of the system IDs, so it's not an order
 that was picked specifically for this purpose - eg, the Advanced Edition
 systems are all at the end)


== Crew teleporting ==

First, when the ship is created, one of three boarding modes is selected:
* None, which seems to be set if there wasn't a boardingAI tag in the ship blueprint
* Sabotage, used by most ships
* Invasion, used by the flagship

Sabotage sends half the crew, while invasion sends 3/4 of the crew. Both round down.
The number of crew that should stay behind is then calculated from this number.

This also sets some flags on the crew: in sabotage mode, the crew's minimum health
is set to 25% (in the BoardingGoal constructor), while for invasion there isn't
a minimum health.

To send crew, first ShipAI::OnLoop calculates the number of boarders to be sent.
This is the number of (friendly) crew abord the ship, minus the number that should
stay behind, as calculated above (this should mean that if you kill crew abord the
enemy ship, they'll try to teleport at least one of their boarders back).

Once the required number of crew are on the teleporter, they'll be sent over. There's
a counter for how many times the teleporter is used, and once it reaches 3 then no
more crew will be teleported over.

To teleport crew back, first ShipAI::RequiredEvac checks whether to force a teleport:
* The ship is escaping, and has less than 15 seconds left on it's escape timer
* There are three or more completely broken systems on the (AI-controlled) ship

Next, CrewAI::ReadyForEvac finds the room to teleport crew from. It goes through the
crew on the player's ship, finding the first one where:
* The crewmember is not controllable by the player
* The crewmember is not a drone
* The crewmember is acting as an intruder (mind-controlled player crew appear to count)
* Either the crewmember is below their minimum health, or RequiredEvac is forcing a teleport

The crew will then be teleported from this room.
